Lyell, James P. R., (James Patrick Ronaldson), 1871-1948
A collection of writings chiefly by Honorius Augustodunensis.

Honorius of Autun, Speculum ecclesiae (ff. 1r-167v). Honorius of Autun, De cognitione uerae uitae (ff. 168r-185r). Hugh of Saint-Victor, De archa Noe (ff. 185r-191r). Honorius of Autun (?), Short quaestiones (ff. 191r-192r). Honorius of Autun, De libero arbitrio (ff. 192r-193v). Honorius of Autun, De animae exilio et patria (ff. 193v-195r). Honorius of Autun (?), De legione (ff. 195r-195v).  Honorius of Autun, Liber duodecim quaestionum (ff. 195v-198v). Honorius of Autun, De decem plagis Aegypti spiritualiter (ff. 199r-199v). Honorius of Autun, Quid vasa honoris et quid vasa contumeliae (ff. 200r-202r). Honorius of Autun, De claustrali vita (ff. 202r-202v). Honorius of Autun, Quid sit scala ad caelum (ff. 202v-203v). Rupert of Deutz, Quaestio utrum monachis liceat praedicare (ff. 203v-204r). Honorius of Autun, Quod monachis liceat praedicare (ff. 204r-205v). Honorius of Autun, Quaestiones theologicae (ff. 205v-206v). Honorius of Autun, Quaestiones octo de angelo et homine (ff. 206v-209v). Honorius of Autun, Summa gloria (ff. 209v-216v). Honorius of Autun, Scala coeli maior (ff. 216v-221v). Honorius of Autun, Sententias patrum de libero arbitrio (ff. 222r-223v). Honorius of Autun, Inevitabile (ff. 223v-236v). Four short pieces (ff. 236v-237v). Honorius of Autun, Sacramentarium (ff. 237v-272r). Further short pieces (ff. 272v-273v). Sermons (ff. 273v-274v). 12th-15th century scribbles (f. 274v).

215–35 × 135–45 mm.: 28–33 long lines, apart from fol. 140v–150v which are written in two columns, ruled in pencil or crayon apart from fol. 58–65v (quire viii) and fol. 165–166v, apparently ruled with a hard point.

Written in several hands in Austria (probably at Lambach) in the third quarter of the 12th century. There are many contemporary corrections and insertions. Some of the insertions and marginal captions by the scribes, describing the contents of the text, are enclosed in frames of red. There are also marginalia in 12th–15th-century hands.

1⁸ (+ a leaf added after 3), 2⁸–19⁸, 20⁸ (+ 1 leaf added after 3 and another after 5), 21⁴ (4 cancelled), 22⁸–26⁸, 27⁸ (8 cancelled), 28⁸ (8 cancelled), 29⁸–34⁸, 35⁴, 36² (1 cancelled): quires 1–18 numbered in roman numerals at the end; quires 23–4 numbered II and III at the beginning; quire 29 numbered I at the end.

The MS. has a series of fine initials, mostly of the vinescroll type, drawn mainly in red but with further details in lilac or light-brown ink, sometimes with parts washed in yellow or green. Some of the initials have zoomorphic features: birds (fols. 1r, 1v, 6v, 44v, 75r, 192r, 209v), monsters (fols. 34r, 44v, 55r, 97v) and a hare (fol. 108v); others have figures: the risen Christ (fol. 58v), St. John the Baptist (fols. 78v, 95r: freestanding figures); heads: fol. 70r, 73r, 86r (Christ and St. Mary Magdalene), 87v (St. James), in (St. Cecilia), 113v (St. Andrew), 117r (St. Thomas), 135v (a monk). On fol. 168r is a figure of a monk, possibly intended to be Honorius himself.

Monastic binding: original thick wooden boards, covered in 15th cent, in white leather with traces of tooling (15th century?), plaited head and tail bands. Remains of two clasps (15th century?, modern straps), traces of bosses; two labels removed from upper cover. On the early bindings of Lambach see K. Holter in Gutenberg Jahrbuch, 1954, p. 280.

Formerly MS. xliii in the library of the Benedictine abbey of Lambach in Austria – the shelfmark ‘M. Memb. xliii’ (early 19th cent.) is on the spine, where there are also two earlier labels, now illegible. Mentioned in a list of books from the Lambach library made c. 1210, pr. by K. Holter, ‘Zwei Bibliotheksverzeichnisse des 13 Jh.’, M.I.Ö.G. 64 (1956), 273; see also K. Holter ‘Stift Lambach. Die Hss. und Inkunabeln’, Österreichische Kunsttopographie xxxiv, ii (1959), 239. Bought by Lyell in March 1942 from A. Rosenthal; see J. Rosenthal, Kat. 90 cit., no. 145 and Taf. lii (fol. 44v). James P. R. Lyell, 1871–1948. Chosen as one of the hundred manuscripts bequeathed to the Bodleian by Lyell in 1948.
Description adapted from A. de la Mare, Catalogue of the Medieval Manuscripts Bequeathed to the Bodleian Library Oxford by James P. R. Lyell (1971); with additions by Andrew Dunning.
